			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2023</a> keynote:</span><br><i>Artificial Languages are Dead. Long Live Artificial Languages!</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/CristinaVideiraLopes.html">Cristina Videira Lopes</a></h2>
<ul><li>URL: <a href="https://2023.splashcon.org/details/sle-2023/21/Artificial-Languages-are-Dead-Long-Live-Artificial-Languages-">https://2023.splashcon.org/details/sle-2023/21/Artificial-Languages-are-Dead-Long-Live-Artificial-Languages-</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6c.html"><span class="tagM">T6C: SLE-for-AI</span></a><ul><li> The keynote is explicitly about how AI/LLMs change the relationship between programming and AI—i.e., language engineering for an AI-shaped software development world (including education implications).
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4g.html"><span class="tagL">T4G: AI-for-SLE</span></a><ul><li> LLMs doing translation from natural language/specifications to code is AI-driven automation directly affecting language use and tooling.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6d.html"><span class="tagL">T6D: Synergies</span></a><ul><li> The framing is broadly cross-cutting (practice + fundamental notions of programming + CS education), i.e., a field-level synthesis/agenda piece.
</li></ul></li></ul>
